2026-04-16 12:36:12 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Sensor-Operated Relay (Control Module)'] hypothesis_explanation="Although the relay is visually closed and nominal continuity is measured during manual inspection, the persistent low voltage at the output terminals of the Control Module (both at ~0.36V and 0V) during the system's operating cycle—despite a steady 12V supply at its input—indicates a failure to pass voltage through the relay contacts. This suggests that the relay contacts may be internally degraded (e.g., high contact resistance, oxidation, or mechanical wear) and fail under load, leading to effective voltage drop across the relay even when it is nominally 'closed.' Temporary restoration after cycling likely corresponds to intermittent contact within the relay, presenting as the brief 'off' and 'on' cycles of the main lamp. Replacing the relay is recommended as the most likely resolution."
